From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-13
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v96 — engine reset in ndo_open so HW refetches descriptors

v95 boot: netdev mts0 → enp0s20f1, carrier ON via PHY-derived v94 fix,
admin UP, LOWER_UP all good.  But ping fails 100%, TX counters stay 0
even on attempted ARP send.

Critical observation: when host pings PS4, an RX_AVAIL IRQ fires on the
PS4 side (pattern 0x00040040 in histogram increments) — HW IS receiving
the packet electrically.  But NAPI poll never delivers it to the netdev
RX counters.

Hypothesis (now patched): probe path starts the RX/TX engines while
ring memory is still freshly dma_alloc_coherent-zero-filled.  HW
fetches descriptors once at engine-enable and caches them: buf_lo=0
across all RX descriptors.  When ndo_open later re-initializes the
rings with valid SKB DMA addresses, HW does NOT refetch — packets get
written to physical address 0 (or just dropped).  The RX IRQ fires
because HW saw a frame on the wire, but the descriptor never marks
OWN=1 in our ring → NAPI sees nothing to do.

Fix: in ndo_open, STOP the engines, re-init rings, re-program the
descriptor ring base addresses, then restart engines.  HW is forced
to refetch descriptors with the new addresses.

The probe-time engine start stays in place to keep PHY/MAC link
detection working through to v95's PHY-derived carrier signaling.
On the first ip link set up, engines get cycled cleanly.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -1322,6 +1322,21 @@
 static int mts_open(struct net_device *ndev)
 {
 	struct mts *mts = netdev_priv(ndev);
+	u32 tx_ctrl_before, rx_ctrl_before;
+
+	/* v96: STOP engines BEFORE re-filling rings.  HW caches descriptor
+	 * state after first read at engine-enable time; if it sampled the
+	 * old zero-filled rings (probe-time engine start), it never refetches
+	 * even after we update buf_lo with real SKB DMA addresses.  Stop
+	 * engines → re-init rings → re-program base addresses → restart
+	 * engines.  This forces HW to fetch the new descriptor contents.
+	 */
+	tx_ctrl_before = readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+	rx_ctrl_before = readl(mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL);
+	writel(tx_ctrl_before & ~0x1u, mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+	writel(rx_ctrl_before & ~0x1u, mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL);
+	(void)readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
+	mdelay(5);
 
 	mts_rings_init(mts);
 
@@ -1335,8 +1350,13 @@
 	napi_enable(&mts->napi);
 	netif_start_queue(ndev);
 
-	/* Re-kick engines so HW notices the new ring contents.  bit 0 of
-	 * the respective CTRL register enables the engine. */
+	dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+		 "v96: ndo_open engine-reset (TX 0x%08x->0x%08x RX 0x%08x->0x%08x)\n",
+		 tx_ctrl_before, readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL),
+		 rx_ctrl_before, readl(mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL));
+
+	/* Start engines fresh.  bit 0 of the respective CTRL register
+	 * enables the engine. */
 	writel(readl(mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL) | 0x1, mts->bar + MTS_TX_CTRL);
 	writel(readl(mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL) | 0x1, mts->bar + MTS_RX_CTRL);
 
